{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Wyz4QneqdLf8RS8t6USRxa","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The current never reaches 100nA in the DC sweep. This is because the PMOS turns on when Vgs goes negative (gate below source). But in our sweep, we're sweeping Vgs (the gate voltage) from 0 to 1.8V while the source is at VDD=1.8V. When gate = 0V, Vgs = 0 - 1.8 = -1.8V (maximum |Vgs|). When gate = 1.8V, Vgs = 0V (off).\n\nBut the Id should be positive (drain current) when the device is on. \n\nAh, I see the issue now—for PMOS with the drain at 0.9V and source at 1.8V, current flows from source to drain, which means the measured Id is actually negative in SPICE convention. That's probably why the measurement isn't hitting the expected 100nA value. Let me check what the actual current values are showing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":238,"cache_read_input_tokens":195333,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":238},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01e4b3b1-6a11-48e6-b3e7-40758ef8985d","uuid":"a2b3e9ad-ec72-48b1-8f02-fbc71fe9fc02"}
